      "snowpackStructure": {
        "comment": "Hard wind slabs are lying on top of a weakly bonded old snowpack in particular on west, north and east facing slopes above approximately 2200 m. The snowpack will be subject to considerable local variations. <br/> <br/> Outgoing longwave radiation during the night will be quite good at times. The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust. In steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface. On extremely steep sunny slopes the snowpack will soften rapidly. Sunshine and high temperatures will give rise as the day progresses to increasing and thorough wetting of the snowpack. <br/> <br/> On steep sunny slopes at low and intermediate altitudes hardly any snow is lying."
      },
